### 7. Updates (Company Announcements)

**Model:** `Update.js` — company + workspace scoped, typed announcements, priority, `readBy[]`, reactions, `isPinned`

| Dimension | Assessment |
|---|---|
| Feature definition | 🟡 Nascent. Model is defined but thin. |
| Expected behaviour | Admin/Owner posts announcements; all workspace members see them; react/read tracking |
| Current architecture | Routes at `/api/updates` |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No socket emission when a new Update is created. Recipients won't see it in real-time. |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ `readBy[]` is a flat array — at scale (50+ users) this becomes a large document. Should be a separate `UpdateRead` collection or use sparse tracking. |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ Permission guard: who can post Updates? No confirmed role check at the route level visible in audit. Only `Owner` and `Admin` should be allowed. |
| **Security risk** | 🟡 `mentions[]` array — no validation that mentioned users belong to the company |
| **Edge cases** | `pinnedUntil` date — no cron or TTL to auto-unpin when date passes |

---

### 8. Huddles (Real-time Voice/Video)

**Socket handler:** `huddles.socket.js` — start/join/leave/end/audio_toggle

| Dimension | Assessment |
|---|---|
| Feature definition | 🔴 **Signaling layer only.** The socket handler manages presence/signaling but there is NO WebRTC peer connection setup, ICE candidate exchange, SDP offer/answer, or media server integration (e.g. Mediasoup, LiveKit). |
| Expected behaviour | Users join a voice channel, can speak to each other in real-time |
| Current architecture | Socket events for `huddle:start/join/leave/end/audio_toggle`. Rooms named `huddle:<huddleId>`. |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No WebRTC signaling (offer/answer/ICE candidates). Without this, audio/video cannot flow between peers. |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No authorization: any authenticated socket can call `huddle:join` with any `huddleId` — there is no check that the user has access to the associated channel |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No persistent `Huddle` model. Session is entirely in-memory — if server restarts, all huddle state is lost. |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ `socket.user.username` is read in `huddle:start` handler but the socket auth only attaches `{ id: decoded.sub }` — username will always be `'Unknown'` |
| **Security risk** | 🔴 No membership check: user can join any huddle without being a channel member |
| **Reliability risk** | 🔴 No reconnection handling — if a user's socket drops mid-huddle, there's no mechanism to rejoin the WebRTC session |
| **Status** | 🔴 **Not functional as a real voice/video system. Requires foundational WebRTC work.** |

---

### 9. Chttrix Intelligence (AI Layer)

**Routes:** `/api/ai` — `src/features/ai/ai.routes.js`

| Dimension | Assessment |
|---|---|
| Feature definition | AI-assisted actions within conversations |
| Current architecture | Routes registered. `utils/aiActions.js` exists. Socket emission fix was recently applied (channel room naming). |
| **Known issue** | `io.to(channelId)` was recently changed to `io.to(\`channel:${channelId}\`)` — verify this fix is in the deployed branch |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No rate limiting on AI endpoints — risk of excessive LLM API costs if abused |
| **Missing logic** | ❌ No per-user or per-workspace AI quota enforcement |
| **Security risk** | 🟡 Prompt injection risk — if user message content is directly passed to the LLM without sanitization |
| **Maturity** | 🟡 Unknown full feature set without reading `ai.routes.js` and `ai.controller.js` |

